    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="901"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d901">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 851.4054/43</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        French Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_JJJ1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jusserand</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 21, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor further to refer to your
                    note of September 26, 1919, and my reply note of October 9, 1919,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d901fn1">Not printed.</note> in regard to the proposed bill relative
                    to the marriage of American soldiers and sailors to French women abroad.</p>
                <p>In this connection I beg to inform you that I am now in receipt of a letter from
                    the War Department of this Government, in which it is stated that the draft of
                    the bill referred to in your note of September 26, 1919, has been submitted to
                    Congress with a request for early enactment.<note n="2" xml:id="d901fn2">A bill
                        “To regulate the marriage of persons in the military and naval forces of the
                        United States in foreign countries, and for other purposes” (S. 3245, 66th
                        Cong., 2d sess.), passed the Senate Jan. 19, 1920, but was not passed by the
                            <persName corresp="#p_HEM1">House</persName> of Representatives.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
